  1. We know that \(s_{n} \mid \theta \sim \operatorname{Binomial}(n, \theta)\), then \[ \operatorname{Pr}\left(s_{n} \mid \theta\right)=\frac{n !}{k !\left(n-s_{n}\right) !} \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}}, \text { for } s_{n}=0,1,2, \ldots, n \] and the likelihood function is \[ L\left(\theta \mid s_{n},A\right) \propto \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}} \] Considering Prior A:\(~\theta \sim \operatorname{Uniform}(0,1)\), which is equivalent to Prior B:\(~\theta \sim \operatorname{Beta}(a, b)\) with \(a=1\) and \(b=1\). Therefore \[ p(\theta \mid A)=\frac{\Gamma(a+b)}{\Gamma(a) \Gamma(b)} \theta^{a-1}(1-\theta)^{b-1} \] for \(a=1\) and \(b=1\). Calculating now the posterior we have that \[ \begin{align} p(\theta~|s_n, A) & \propto \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}}\theta^{a-1}(1-\theta)^{b-1} \\ & \propto \theta^{a+s_n-1}(1-\theta)^{b+n-s_n-1} \end{align} \] and \((\theta~|(s_n,A)) \sim \operatorname{Beta}(a+s_n,b+n-s_n)\). Hence, \((\theta~|(s_n,A)) \sim \operatorname{Beta}(8,4)\).

  2. Following the same procedure as in item (a), the likelihood function in this case is \[ L\left(\theta \mid s_{n},B\right) \propto \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}} \] and now considering the Prior B:\(~\theta \sim \operatorname{Beta}(a, b)\) with \(a=4\) and \(b=2\), we have that \[ \begin{align} p(\theta~|s_n, B) & \propto \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}}\theta^{a-1}(1-\theta)^{b-1} \\ & \propto \theta^{a+s_n-1}(1-\theta)^{b+n-s_n-1} \end{align} \] Substituting \(a=4, b=2, n=10\) and \(s_n=7\), \((\theta~|s_n, B) \sim \operatorname{Beta}(11,5)\).

  1. Now we have the prior C:\(\log (\theta /(1-\theta)) \sim \operatorname{Normal}\left(\mu, \sigma^{2}\right)\), then \[ p(\theta \mid C)=\left(2 \pi \sigma^{2}\right)^{-1 / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{1}{2 \sigma^{2}}\left[\log \left(\frac{\theta}{1-\theta}\right)-\mu\right]^{2}\right\} \frac{1}{\theta(1-\theta)} \] In order to calculate the posterior we have to compute \[ p\left(\theta \mid s_{n}, C\right)=\frac{\left.p\left(s_{n} \mid \theta\right)\right) p(\theta \mid C)}{\int_{0}^{1} p\left(s_{n} \mid \theta\right) p(\theta \mid C) d \theta}=\frac{\left.p\left(s_{n} \mid \theta\right)\right) p(\theta \mid C)}{\operatorname{Pr}\left(s_{n} \mid C\right)} \] Note that in the expression the prior density and the likelihood function fail to conjugate, then we might use Monte Carlo Integration to approximate \(\operatorname{Pr}\left(s_{n} \mid C\right)\) \[ p\left(\theta \mid s_{n}, C\right) \propto \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}}\exp \left\{-\frac{1}{2 \sigma^{2}}\left[\log \left(\frac{\theta}{1-\theta}\right)-\mu\right]^{2}\right\} \frac{1}{\theta(1-\theta)} \] calling \(g(\theta) \equiv \theta^{s_{n}}(1-\theta)^{n-s_{n}}\exp \left\{-\frac{1}{2 \sigma^{2}}\left[\log \left(\frac{\theta}{1-\theta}\right)-\mu\right]^{2}\right\} \frac{1}{\theta(1-\theta)}\) we have \[ p\left(\theta \mid s_{n}, C\right) \propto \dfrac{g(\theta)}{\int g(\theta)d\theta} \] The objective is to compute \(E_{q}[h(\theta)]=\int h(\theta) q(\theta) d \theta\). \[ I = \dfrac{g(\theta)}{\int g(\theta)d\theta} = \dfrac{\int \theta h(\theta)q(\theta)d\theta}{\int h(\theta)q(\theta)d\theta} \] where we have that \(\theta^{(1)},...,\theta^{(m)} \sim q(\theta) \equiv \operatorname{Uniforme}(0,1)\) then, \[ I = \dfrac{E_q(h_1(\theta))}{E_q(h_2(\theta))} \] where \(h_1(\theta) = \dfrac{\theta g(\theta)}{q(\theta)}\). Defining now \(I_{MC} = \dfrac{\dfrac{1}{M}\sum^m_{i=1} h_1(\theta^{(i)})}{\dfrac{1}{M}\sum^m_{i=1} h_2(\theta^{(i)})}\) we have that \[ I_{MC} \to I ~~\textbf{when} ~~ M \to \infty \] Computing the normalizing constant, the prior predictive, via Monte Carlo integration:

prob = function(theta,mu,sig2){
  dnorm(log(theta/(1-theta)),mu,sqrt(sig2))/(theta*(1-theta))
}
thetas = seq(0.001,0.999,by=0.001)

  1. Recall that the mean for a beta distribution is \(E[x] = \dfrac{a}{a+b}\) and the variance is \(V[x] = \dfrac{ab}{(a+b)^2(a+b+1)}\). Therefore, according to item (a) and (b) we can compute the mean and variance using \(E[x] = \dfrac{a + s_n}{a+b+n}\) and \(V[x] = \dfrac{(a+s_n)(b+n-s_n)}{(a+b+n)^2(a+b+n+1)}\)

M = 10000

# SIR step 2 -  Computing weights (unormalized)

numerator = (theta^7*(1-theta)^3)*prob(theta,0,3)
denominator = 1
w=numerator/denominator
#normalizing
w = w/sum(w)

# SIR step 3 - resampling the set {theta[1],...,theta[M]} with weights w[1],...,w[M]
theta1 = sample(theta,replace=TRUE,size=M,prob=w)

Calculating the posterior \[ \begin{align} p(\theta | s_n, D) & \propto L(\theta | s_n)p(\theta|D) \\ & \propto \theta^{s_n}(1-\theta)^{(n-s_n)} \left[ 0.8\dfrac{\Gamma(10)}{\Gamma(7)\Gamma(3)}\theta^2(1-\theta)^6 + 0.2\dfrac{\Gamma(10)}{\Gamma(3)\Gamma(7)}\theta^6(1-\theta)^2\right] \\ & \propto \theta^{s_n}(1-\theta)^{(n-s_n)} \left[ 0.8\theta^2(1-\theta)^6 + 0.2\theta^6(1-\theta)^2\right] \equiv g(\theta) \end{align} \] Normalizing we find that \[ p(\theta | s_n, D) = \dfrac{\theta^{s_n}(1-\theta)^{(n-s_n)} \left[ 0.8\theta^6(1-\theta)^2 + 0.2\theta^2(1-\theta)^6\right]}{\int_0^1 (\theta^{s_n}(1-\theta)^{(n-s_n)} \left[ 0.8\theta^6(1-\theta)^2 + 0.2\theta^2(1-\theta)^6\right])d\theta} \]

\[ p(\theta | s_n, D) = \dfrac{g(\theta)}{\int g(\theta)d\theta} \] Computing the expectation \[ \begin{align} E(\theta | s_n,D) &= \int \theta p(\theta | s_n, D)d\theta \\ &= \dfrac{\int \theta g(\theta)d\theta }{\int g(\theta)d\theta} \end{align} \]
